          "body": "After the honor parade, verse 12 offers one of the Bible's most understated observations: 'Then Mordecai returned to the king's gate.' He was honored publicly by the most powerful king in the world and went back to his post. He did not leverage the moment, did not seek an audience with the king, did not begin building a counter-strategy against Haman. The king's gate is where he began (2:19), where he sat in mourning when the decree was signed (4:2), and where he returns now. This pattern — faithful presence in an ordinary station, through threat and through honor — is the shape of Mordecai's character across the whole book. It is also the shape of the godly life under sovereign providence: you serve where you are placed, trust the One who arranges the overnight reversals, and return to your post. The contrast with Haman's panicked flight home (6:12) could not be sharper."
