        "excerpt": "The king said to him, 'What is to be done for the man whom the king desires to honor?' And Haman said to himself, 'Whom would the king desire to honor more than me?'",
        "body": "Verses 4-6 contain the chapter's central dramatic irony, constructed through timing and psychology. Haman's arrival in the outer court (6:4) is simultaneous with the king's question about who is available — a convergence the narrator signals with *hinneh* (behold, 6:5), a Hebrew particle that draws the reader's attention to an unexpected or significant appearance. Haman has come to request Mordecai's execution. The king summons him to consult about Mordecai's honor. Neither knows what the other is about to say.\n\nThe king's question — 'What is to be done for the man whom the king desires to honor?' — is deliberately unspecified. The Hebrew *chaphets* (delight, desire) is the same verb used of God's delight in His covenant people elsewhere in the Old Testament (Psalm 147:11; Isaiah 62:4). Here it describes royal favor without naming its object, which is the structural trap that catches Haman. He is asked a general question and returns a specific assumption.\n\nHaman's inner monologue (6:6) is the only moment in the chapter when the narrator grants direct access to a character's thought. 'Whom would the king desire to honor more than me?' — the Hebrew *yoter* ('more than') places Haman at the apex of a hierarchy he has constructed entirely in his own imagination. He is not lying; he genuinely believes it. This is what Proverbs 16:18 calls a 'haughty spirit before stumbling' — the pride that has so thoroughly colonized the interior that reality cannot penetrate it. Jonathan Edwards, in his *Religious Affections*, notes that the most dangerous self-deception is not the kind one performs for others but the kind one has performed so thoroughly that even the internal audience is convinced.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chaphets* (delight, desire) — used of God's covenantal pleasure in His people in Psalm 147:11 and Isaiah 62:4. Its use here for royal favor is ironic: the king's delight, which Haman assumes centers on himself, is about to be directed entirely toward the man Haman has targeted for death. *Nadad* (fled, v.1) — sleep as an active agent abandoning the king, a vivid Hebrew idiom for restlessness."
